2 (7) "Level 3 automated driving system" means an automated driving system that:
3 (a) has the capability to perform on a sustained basis the entire dynamic driving task within its
4 operational design domain; and
5 (b) requires a fallback ready user to operate the vehicle after the automated driving system issues
6 a request for the fallback ready user to intervene or a system failure occurs.
7 (8) "Level 4 automated driving system" means an automated driving system feature that, without
8 any expectation a human driver will respond to a request to intervene, has the capability to perform:
9 (a) on a sustained basis the entire dynamic driving task within its operational design domain; and
10 (b) any maneuvers necessary to achieve a minimal risk condition in response to:
11 (i) an exit from the operational design domain of the automated driving system; or
12 (ii) a system failure.
13 (9) "Level 5 automated driving system" means an automated driving system feature that, without
14 any expectation a human driver will respond to a request to intervene, has the capability to perform:
15 (a) on a sustained basis the entire dynamic driving task under all conditions that can reasonably
16 be managed by a human driver; and
17 (b) any maneuvers necessary to respond to a system failure.
18 (10) "Operational design domain" means the operating conditions under which an automated driving
19 system or a feature of an automated driving system is specifically designed to function, including:
20 (a) speed-range, environmental, geographical, and time-of-day restrictions; or
21 (b) the requisite presence or absence of certain traffic or roadway conditions.
22 (11) "Public highways of this state" has the same meaning as provided in 60-1-201.
23
24 NEW SECTION. Section 4. Use of automated driving systems. (1) A vehicle with automated
25 driving systems level 1, level 2, and level 3 may be used on the public highways of this state.
26 (2) A vehicle with automated driving systems level 4 and level 5 may be used on the public
27 highways of this state subject to limitations established by department rulemaking as provided in [section 5].
